      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moment of Decision: The Vote on China Trade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert H Lavitt letter disputes May 21 editorial criticizing organized labor for urging Congress to vote against China's entry into World Trade Organization (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Labor and the China Vote'' (editorial, May 21) criticizes organized labor for urging Congress to vote against establishing permanent normal trading status with China. But I don't hear organized labor crying for protectionism. Rather, I hear calls for fair trade and for rules of engagement that give American workers a chance.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Labor and the China Vote'' (editorial, May 21) criticizes organized labor for urging Congress to vote against establishing permanent normal trading status with China. But I don't hear organized labor crying for protectionism. Rather, I hear calls for fair trade and for rules of engagement that give American workers a chance.</p>
        <p>Why should we invite countries that violently suppress dissent and civil liberties, operate prison labor factories and outlaw the formation of independent unions to enjoy trade privileges? Just as multinational corporations seek enforceable protections for intellectual property and against copyright infringement, American workers seek an international system that safeguards basic human rights for their counterparts overseas.</p>
        <p>ROBERT H. LAVITT  Seattle, May 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a labor and employment lawyer.</p>
      </block>
